snippet.title: AfS Live: Food and nutrition security during the global pandemic
snippet.description: Abebe Menkir has been breeding maize for over 20 years. He currently heads the maize breeding department at CGIAR-IITA. Menkir talks to Patricia Nanteza about the need to increase agricultural resilience in the face of climate change and global pandemics such as COVID-19. Maize, especially the orange variety, can provide the vitamin A necessary to boost immunity and also meet the body’s energy requirements.

snippet.title: AfS Live: Africa's women farmers: Innovating in the time of COVID
snippet.description: Four African women farmers discuss the innovative measures they are using to get their crops to the public despite Africa's lockdowns and travel restrictions during the COVID pandemic.

snippet.title: AfS Live: Conspiracy Theories in the Time of COVID
snippet.description: Bright Simons, founder and president of mPedigree; Whitney Phillips, Syracuse University; Stephan Lewandowsky, University of Bristol; Joanne Miller, University of Delaware; John Cook, George Mason University and moderator Mark Lynas discuss the nature and appeal of conspiracy theories and how to deal with them.

snippet.title: AfS Live: Top 5 Most Promising COVID-19 Vaccine Projects
snippet.description: More than 100 vaccine efforts are currently underway in the global push to stop the COVID-19 pandemic, according to the World Health Organization. Which are most likely to work? And how long will it take? Science writer Mark Lynas and AfS Fellow Modesta Nnedinso Abugu take a look at the five most promising candidates.

snippet.title: AfS Live: Navigating the new USDA rule on genetic engineering
snippet.description: Biotech policy expert Greg Jaffe explains the new US Department of Agriculture rule on genetic engineering and answers questions about the topic in this AfS Live! presentation.

snippet.title: AfS Live: Brazil, COVID and the rise of anti-science sentiment
snippet.description: Natalia Pasternak, director of Instituto Questão de Ciência (Question of Science Institute) — Brazil’s first institute to promote skepticism and rational thinking —  and Guatemalan attorney Pablo Orozco discuss Brazil's response to the COVID-19 pandemic and the rise of anti-science sentiment in the country.

snippet.title: AfS Live: Africa Reports on COVID, Conspiracies and Crops
snippet.description: In this live webinar recorded on June 15, 2020, three Alliance for Science correspondents — Nkechi Isaac, Joseph Opoku Gakpo and Verenardo Meeme — discussed the current situation in Nigeria, Ghana and Kenya, respectively, in response to COVID-19, associated conspiracy theories and food security. Joan Conrow, AfS managing editor, served as moderator. See the lineup of upcoming webinars at https://allianceforscience.cornell.edu/alliance-for-science-live/events/.

snippet.title: Man's best friend helps in fight against COVID-19
snippet.description: Researchers in Finland and elsewhere are training dogs to detect the coronavirus and preliminary results indicate the dogs are better, faster and cheaper than current detection methods. Read more: https://allianceforscience.cornell.edu/blog/2020/05/dogs-sniff-covid19/

snippet.title: How Bt brijnal made Bangladesh a global 'role model'
snippet.description: Since entering the market in 2014, Bt brinjal has helped smallholder farmers in Bangladesh achieve higher yields, a 60 percent reduction in pesticide costs and a six-fold increase in net returns. The crop has been so successful that the USDA Foreign Agricultural Service recently released a report that hailed Bangladesh as "a role model of acceptance and advancement of modern agricultural biotechnology."

snippet.title: Alliance for Science Global Leadership Fellows - Biotechnology as a Tool for Global Food Security
snippet.description:
The Cornell Alliance for Science seeks to promote access to scientific innovation as a means of enhancing food security, improving environmental sustainability, and raising the quality of life globally.

We are building a global network of science allies who share our commitment to solve complex global hunger issues by leveraging advances in agriculture, including biotechnology.

The Cornell Alliance for Science Global Leadership Fellows Program is a 12-week intensive training course held on the Cornell University campus in Ithaca, NY, USA. It is designed to equip and empower emerging international leaders who are committed to advocating for science-based communications and access to scientific innovation in their home countries. The training focuses on strategic planning, grassroots organizing, and innovative communications with a strong focus on stories of science and effective communications around agricultural biotechnology. Throughout the course, Fellows work to build comprehensive strategic communications plans promoting access to scientific innovation in their local contexts while engaged in seminars and workshops led by international thought leaders and subject matter experts, weekly colloquia organized and led by Fellows, and field trips to New York State farms and state-of-the-art research facilities.

https://allianceforscience.cornell.edu/education/global-leadership-fellowship/
